{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/introducing-linear-regression-least-squares-the-easy-way-3a8b38565560", "time": 1683002976.305759, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/introducing-linear-regression-least-squares-the-easy-way-3a8b38565560/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Introducing Linear Regression (Least Squares) the Easy Way | by Shivangi Sareen | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Introducing Linear Regression (Least Squares) the Easy Way", "description": "The linear least squares supervised fitting technique is the simplest and most commonly applied form of linear regression and provides a solution to the problem of finding the best fitting straight\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["The linear least squares supervised fitting technique is the simplest and most commonly applied form of linear regression and provides a solution to the problem of finding the best fitting straight line through a set of points.", "Our general linear regression model looks like this-", "The input is a feature vector (x1, x2, \u22ef , xk)The output is a scalar yThe model links the output to the input feature vector with a linear relationship:", "In linear regression, without the bias term our solution has to go through the origin. That is, when all of our features are zero, our predicted value would also have to be zero. However, that may not be the answer the training data suggests. Adding a bias weight that does not depend on any of the features allows the hyperplane described by the learned weights to more easily fit data that doesn\u2019t pass through the origin.", "Now, consider a very basic linear model with two variables. Temperature is the independent variable and we wish to find out the effect of temperature on sales (dependent variable).", "The twelve data points are in the form of (x,Y). The x-coordinate represents the temperature in degree Celsius and the Y-coordinate represents the sales in dollars. The very first step is to visualise the data \u2014 graph it (as shown above). Graphing is possible in this case since we are considering only two variables.", "Our aim is to find a line that is the best fit for the above data, like above.", "Any line is of the form:", "Where m is the slope of the line (the tan of the angle made by the line with the x axis calculated counter-clockwise) and c is the y-intercept.", "Here y represents sales for a particular temperature x.", "So, our best fit line will also be of the form y = mx + c.", "x1: actual value of temperature in degree Celsius", "Y1: actual value of sales in dollars corresponding to x1", "y1 = m*x1 + c: predicted value of sales corresponding to x1 according to the best fit line", "E1 is the first error term.", "Both shapes in this picture are \u201clinear\u201d:", "\u201cLinear\u201d in statistics is used to describe the parameters in the model we are using. Linear means that the response (y variable) is expected to be a linear combination of explanatory variables (either discrete or continuous). Linear refers to the explanatory variables being additive.", "When we say the model is linear, that statement is actually incomplete. What needs to be specified and checked for linear regression is if the model is linear w.r.t the parameters (w0, w1, w2, \u2026 ,wk).", "Coming back to the errors. Our objective is to reduce these errors and hence, least squared errors.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Software Engineer @Apple | Reader | Writer | The Sustainable Edit"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F3a8b38565560&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fintroducing-linear-regression-least-squares-the-easy-way-3a8b385